Atomic variables, and concurrent collections.

For the simple case of a single value updated by many threads, there is something even better than a lock: the atomic classes, from the java-util-concurrent-atomic package. Instead of blocking, they use a see-pee-you-level instruction called compare-and-swap, which updates a value atomically in hardware, and they never make a thread wait. An atomic integer gives you increment-and-get, a genuinely atomic plus plus, and compare-and-set, which writes a new value only if the current value still matches what you expected. There is also update-and-get, which applies a function atomically, and an atomic reference for object values. For a hot counter, an atomic integer is faster and simpler than any lock.

For whole data structures, the story is different. The plain hash map and array list are not thread-safe, and modifying them from several threads at once gives undefined behaviour. The java-util-concurrent package supplies thread-safe replacements designed for high contention. Concurrent hash map replaces hash map, using fine-grained locking so many threads can read and write different parts at once. Copy-on-write array list replaces array list for read-heavy cases, where every write copies the whole backing array, so reads never need a lock. Blocking queue is a producer-consumer hand-off, where put blocks when the queue is full and take blocks when it is empty. And concurrent linked queue is a lock-free first-in-first-out queue.

The two combine beautifully in one classic pattern. A concurrent hash map whose values are atomic integers gives you a safe set of named counters. You call compute-if-absent to lazily create the counter, then increment-and-get on the atomic integer, and the whole thing is correct under heavy concurrency without a single explicit lock.
